# CustodyNote — Project Rules for Cursor

## Project

- CustodyNote is an Electron desktop app for legal custody work
- Stack: Electron + vanilla JS + HTML/CSS + sql.js
- Main process: `main.js` — app lifecycle, IPC handlers, file/OS operations, updater
- Renderer: `app.js` + `renderer/views/*.js` — UI only, communicates via preload bridge
- Preload: `preload.js` — minimal contextBridge API surface
- Packaging: electron-builder, Windows NSIS installer, electron-updater via GitHub Releases
- Do NOT introduce React, Vue, TypeScript, or UI frameworks unless explicitly requested
- Preserve existing architecture unless there is a strong, stated reason to change it

## Cross-platform parity (Mac + Windows)

- One codebase, two builds — custody workflow behaviour must be the same on macOS and Windows
- Do not add platform-specific custody/business logic; only OS integration may differ (see `.cursor/rules/custody-note-cross-platform-parity.mdc`)
- When finishing work, state Mac and Windows impact explicitly

## General coding

- Prefer small, modular functions over large rewrites
- Keep code understandable and maintainable
- Reuse existing patterns where sensible
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies
- Do not invent abstractions unless they solve a real repeated problem
- Match existing code style — look at surrounding code before writing

## Debugging

- Diagnose root cause BEFORE fixing
- Inspect real code paths and trace execution flow — do not guess
- List files inspected, relevant functions, and likely cause before making changes
- Add diagnostic logging where needed before changing behaviour
- For complex bugs: show the execution trace, explain the root cause, then propose the fix

## Electron

- Do not create duplicate app lifecycle handlers (app.whenReady, app.on('window-all-closed'), etc.)
- Do not duplicate IPC listeners — register each ipcMain.handle/on exactly once
- Keep main process and renderer responsibilities clearly separated
- Do not trigger privileged main-process behaviour directly from renderer without IPC
- Explain lifecycle changes clearly — relaunch, quit, restart flows are dangerous
- Guard development-only code with app.isPackaged checks

## Updater (critical — this area has caused production incidents)

- Never initialise autoUpdater more than once
- Never register updater event listeners more than once
- Never call quitAndInstall more than once per update cycle
- Always guard updater logic with app.isPackaged
- Always log every updater event to persistent log (cn-auto-update.log)
- Always persist update state to cn-auto-update-state.json
- Always detect failed version transitions on startup (pending version != current version)
- Always implement loop prevention — if install fails N times, stop retrying
- Never add setInterval-based update checks without cooldown and circuit breaker
- After quitAndInstall, always force app.exit(0) on a timeout to release file locks

## Build / NSIS

- Explain any electron-builder config changes before making them
- Validate install path and permission implications
- Avoid breaking updater compatibility (publish config, latest.yml)
- Prefer safe per-user install (perMachine: false) unless justified
- The custom NSIS script (build/installer.nsh) kills running instances before install — do not remove this
- Test build changes in packaged mode, not just dev mode

## Output

- Before fixing: list files inspected and the root cause
- Explain why the chosen fix is the smallest robust fix
- Provide complete code changes — not vague advice or partial snippets
- After changes: describe how to test and what could still fail

## Do not

- Give generic advice without inspecting actual project code
- Leave multiple competing implementations for the same feature
- Guess root causes — trace first
- Bypass Electron process boundaries
- Create restart/retry loops without circuit breakers
- Modify updater flow without reading the full existing updater code
- Push build config changes without explaining permission and path implications
